{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_knapweed_ver01/data/sn82006551/00340581672/1949032401/0680.xml":{"full_text":"Deny Inter-State\nFreight Rates\nHelena (U.R)\u2014The Montana Board\nof Railroad Commissioners have\ndenied intra-state freight rate in\ncreases sought by the railroads and\nmotor carriers.\nRailroad and motor freight car\nriers each had sought an increase\nof four per cent.\nHearings on the requested in\ncreases were held last January 27\nand 28, and the Board said evidence\nsubmitted at the hearings failed to\ndisclose reasons sufficient to war\nrant granting of increases.\n\nSimultaneously, the Board issued\nan order denying intra-state pas\nsenger fare increases sought by the\nIntermountain Transportation Co.,\nBurlington Transportation Co., the\nNorthwest Greyhound Lines, Inc.,\nand Northland Greyhound Lines,\nInc.\nCharter rate increases sought by\nthose four companies and several\nothers, including Butte and Great\nFalls city lines, were also denied.\nSeven small bus lines wer\u00e9'grant\ned permission to increase their pres\nent rates an average of 10 per cent\nand establish a 25 cent minimum\nrate after they showed at a hearing\nthat they were operating at a loss\nand needed increased fares in order\nto continue to furnish service to the\nareas served by each._\nSPARKPLUG OF PROGRESS\nJ. C. Penney, the head of the\nnational chain store system which\nbears his name, recently commented\non the business outlook,\nwill, of course, be a leveling off in\ncertain lines of merchandise this\nyear,\" he said. \"It's already hap\nBut I don't look for a\nThere's no excuse\n\"There\npemng.\ndrastic break,\nfor a depression or even a mild re\ncession.'\nThose are cheering words, coming\nas they do from a man who has\nseen a great many ups and downs\nin the business cycle, and who has\ndone much to better retailing's con\ntribution to the welfare of the\nAmerican people. But no retailer,\nno matter how small or how large\nhis organization, can afford to sit\nback and wait for the customers to\ncome streaming in. A price con\nserious, quality-conscious public is\ndemanding the utmost in value and\nservice. The good merchant, like\nthe good manufacturer, must offer\na worthwhile product, and he must\nsell it aggressively.\nDuring and just after the war\nmerchandising was relatively static.\nThe shortage of materials forced\nconsumers to accept almost any\nsubstitute. Strict price and other\ncontrols took the edge off competi\ntion. Now a great change has taken\nplace. The list of commodities in\nshort supply is dwindling. The list\nof those in abundance is growing.\nThat means a new sharpening of\ncompetition. It also means success\nwill aomc to those merchants who\nhave the greatest ability and desire\nto serve consumers.\nThe American economy rest upon\nthe place where\nthe retail store\nearnings are exchanged for goods.\nHonest competition is the spark\nplug of its progress, coupled with\nhonest and carefully thought out\nadvertising.\n1949 NONAGRICULTURAL\nEMPLOYMENT SCHEDULED\nMore than eight thousand jobs\nin Montana's non-agricultural in\ndustries evaporated temporarily\nduring the four month period from\nOctober 15, 1948 to February 15,\n1949, according to preliminary es\ntimates prepared by the Unemploy\nment Compensation Commission in\ncooperation with the Bureau of La\nbor Statistics.\nThe job shrinkage amounted to\na decline of 5.8 percent from the\nall-time employment high estab\nlished last October and was 50 per\ncent great ;r than the seasonal\nfhrinkage that occurred during the\ncorresponding period of the pre\nceding winter.\nBarclay Craighead, chairman of\nthe commission, said adverse weath\ner. which broke all existing records\nfor severity, it held responsible for\nmost of the decline which followed\nnormal season trends but to a more\nintensified degree than at any time\nsince pre-war semi-recession years.\nHe said the estimates indicate\nthat despite the loss of 8,000 jobs\nthe February level was still one\nor two percent higher than in Feb\nruary a year ago and that the spring\nPHONE..\n69\nFOR FUEL OIL\nAl Uithof\nOval E Distributor\nPAT'S CARTER\nSERVICE\nemployment upswing which got un\nderway, with the return of fair\nI weather this month is starting from\na higher level than it did a year\nago.\nWith the exception of manufac\nturing, which dropped 700, and\ntransportation, which was un\nchanged, all major industrial cate-.\ngones were up from the level of\nFebruary a year ago Craighead\nsaich Minmg was employing 11 700\nt up 400 c o o n n n stru ct 1 on 6 ,3\u00b00, up 1,200,\nmo 33 200 UP fma ?r\u00abnn'\n\u00abno 100> sen ce industries s 14,800, up\n600 and government 27,900, up 1,\nuuu\n\"All present indications are that\nnon-agncultural employment in\nMontana this year will run close\nthe record level established in\n1948 i he saic and there is t he\npossiblity that they may exceed that\nlevel despite soft spots .that are\nthreatening to develop in lumber\nj n g trade and service\nBETTER HOMES AND\nYARDS CONTEST\nEnter the Better Home and Yards\ncontest before April 15. This is\na free contest and open to all resi\ndents of Libby. Prizes will be\nawarded on the amount of work\nput into your yard or remodeling.\nPrizes will be given in the fol\nlowing divisions; General upkeep\nof home and yard; 1st prize $2.50;\n2nd prize $2.50; 3rd prize evergreen\nshrub. Old and new landscaping:\n1st prize $2.50; 2nd prize $2.50;\n3rd prize, evergreen shrub. Re\nmodeling of older homes: 1st prize,\n$2.*50; 2nd prize $2.50 and 3rd prize\nevergreen shrub.\nAn additional first and second\nprize of $2.50 each will be given\nfor any special work, such as outdoor\nfireplac\u00e7s, pools, rock gardens, or\nnamental fences and so forth.\nGet your applications at Chap\nman's 5c to $1.00 store or call 216-J\nto be entered into the contest. Make\nyour home or yard the prize win\nnei this year. Reporter.\nThe menu of this year's\nMENU DIVERSIFIED\nBoston (U.R) Boston's annual fish\nand game dinner lives up to its\nname.\nevent included rabbit and venison\nstew, moose and buffalo steaks,\nNewfoundland salmon, venison, elk.\ncoon .bear and caribou.\nI\nSewing Machine Repairs\nA SERVICE REPRESENTATIVE OF THE\nSinger Sewing Machine Company\nMissoula, Montana\n312 North Higgins\nWILL BE IN LIBBY AND VICINITY\nEVERY THIRD WEEK\nIf you need service on any make sewing\nmachine just fill out and mail the coupon\noar repair experts will do the rest.\nName\nAddress\nMake of Machine\nSPRING SPECIALS\n6-Piece Living Room Set\nDaveno Rocker\n2 End Tables\n1 Coffee Table\n1 Floor Lamp\n95\n149.\n6-Piece Living Room Set\nDavenport Chair\n2 End Tables (Tiered)\n1 Cocktail Table\n1 Floor Lamp\n95\n99.\nComplete Set In\nBlond Finish\nDaveno Chair\n95\n199.\nFrieze Covered\n2 End Tables\n1 Coffee Table\n1 Floor Lamp\nSECOND HAND SPECIALS\n$65.00\n10.00\n$10.00\n$5.00\nDavenport Chair\nDaveno, only\n2 Club Chairs\n1 Single Bed\n1 Double Bed\n1 Black Walnut Dining Room Table\n1 Round Table\n1 Round Table\n1 Water Heater\n1 Table Model Radio.\n7.50\n$15.00\n10.00\n5.00\n7.50\n$15.00\nSPECIAL\n$40 Trade-in allowance for your old Radio on the\nNew Victor model 8V90 Radio Console\nENNEDY\nFURNITURE MART\nf\nWHO LIFTS THF CHEC K FOR\n\"OPERATION SNOWLIFT?\"\nNow that the states between the\nMissouri and the Rockies have dug\nthemselves out from the packed\nsnows of a three-months' blizzard,\nthe bills for the job are pouring\n1\nin many ot her places,\ntands out the striking con\nbetween the way the Govern\n^as the railways and the\ntreats rival methods of\ntransportation. The railways did\ntheif own sno w-plowing, ice blast\ning anc j ditch-digging\u2014with their\nequipment and at their own\nexpense\u2014while opening up high\nways for trucks was done by Gov\nernment at the taxpayers' expense.\nThe cost of the railway's snow\nfighting will have to be reflected\nin their rates and fares\u2014or defic\niencies in net income. But. the cost\nof clearing highways will not ap\nin charges for truck trans\nInstead it will be con\nm.\nown\npear\nportation.\ncealed in higher taxes, which every\nbody will pay.\nIt just happens, without any rea\nson or logic to explain it, that a\ntradition has grown up* which piles\nall the costs of railway service up\non the rates which railway patrons\nmust pay, while it has become an\naccepted custom with other kinds\nof transportation to shift a large\noart of the costs to the taxpayer.\u2014\nRailway Age.\nj us t how strong is the Russian\neconomy by comparison with that\n0 f the' United States? Just how\nsuccessful have\nleaders b'x-n in restoring their basic j\nindustry after the strains and rav-i\na g e .s of a long war 9\nThesc arc ques tions ol the high- j\ne st importance. Russia's capacity\nio fight again, regardless of ho.v\nlarge her aimies and air forces I\nmay bo. will bo largely determined I\nby her industrial potential\u2014military\npow\u00ab r burns out swiftly unless I\nthere is an unbroken stream of\nupplits to feed it.\nU. S. News World Report dealt j\nwith the Soviet Union's economic\nNewspapers depended upon the\nchange arrival of private letters as\nsources of news during the Revolu\ntionary War._\nECONOMIC HIGHLIGHTS\nthe Communist\nsituation in a recent article whose\nfirst paragraph said: \"Russia is c in\ntinuing to lead from weakness, not\nfrom strength, m her challenge to\nnations of the West. The fact is\nshovn by the condition of Russian\nindustry\ntime\nand\nagriculture at this\nmn k' i zme backed that up\nwith a senes u f revealing statistics.\nRussia's postwar in-1\ndusti'ial comeback has been rela\ntively slow. The output of her fac\nlorie- is .still t! per cent below the\n1940 level. U s. production, by\nconti ast, is now 54 per cent above,\nBritain is also exceeding the pre\nwai ugure.though bv a much small\ner percentage.\nWhen a direct industry-by-indus\ntry comparison is made with this\ncountry.\nRussia's inferiority is\nstriking, She now produces 10 per\ncent as much oil as we do, 18.5 per\ncent as much\nper cent as\nper cent as much coal\u2014all basic\nproducts which have a direct bear\ning on her entire economy. She\nproduces only 3 2 per cent as many\ntrucks and cars, though she is now\nmaking strenuous effort to build up\nher motor industrv.\nelectric power. 23\nmuch steel, and 31\nTo take ex\nw\nam\nTHnumUtiL\n5 H.p. DELUXE TWINS\nk\nr.\n139\n50\nAuto-Rawind \"E-Z\"\nStarter\n2 to 12 Milet Per Hour\nLiberal Trade-In\nAllowed\n2.50 per week, paynbl\u00bb monrWy\nHere's an outboard motor that's iutl \"itching\" to take you\ninto new adventure on your favorite river or lake. Depend\nable, economical and always ready to start Thats\nHIAWATHA\n69 50\n11/2 H.P. HIAWATHA\n3 H. P. HIAWATHA\n$93.50\nGonial\nAUTHORIZED DEALER\nLIBBY, MONTANA\nAny car without new individual, inner-spring\nfront shock suspension is out-of-date!\nI\u00ab\nit\n*n\ni\ni0\nW/\u00e0\na\n\nTh\u00bb Koii.r D\u00bb Lux\u00bb\n\nmm j\na\n\n'V\nS Ri\nDrive the roughest roads!\nEngineered for comfort!\nLess bounce over bumps\nLess side-sway on curves!\nIn a Kaiser you Rot more for your money!\nYou 11 be surprised to learn how little it\ncosts you to drive a Kaiser.\n2088 48\nThe Kaiser Special.$2328-57\n$2509.01\nTo a new distribution of mass and load has been\nso vibra\nThe Kaiser Traveler\nadded a sturdy new frame, an engine\ntion-free you can scarcely hear it, finger tip\nInside you'll find\nThe Kaiser De laxe\n\u2022A new Rainer model, now in production\navailable Boon. White sidewall tire*\u00bb available at\nextra coat. Prices include factory-instaUsd ac\nREADY TO DRIVE. Transporta\nHt\u00abte and local taxea if any) extra. Prices\nject to change without notice.\nsteering, new, longer springs,\nwide, wide seats, deep and soft These are just\na few of the 103 new features in the 1949 Kaiser\nbacked by the HUGGED RELIABILITY\nthree billion\ntion.\naub\nproved by 330,000 owners in over\nmiles of postwar driving.\nKAISER-FRAZIR Dealers everywhere you g